<h3>Prompt Syntaxe</h3>

<p class="italic font-medium text-cyan-300">«Hey I write big breast in my prompt it’s doing nothing! My waifu is flat.»</p>

<p>
	At some point in your prompt, you'll probably want to modulate a particular word more or less strongly. To do this, the interface allows this syntax:
</p>
<p>
	use <code>(big breast:1.1)</code> will be more significant. never go further than 1.3, it's useless, even counterproductive.
</p>
<p class="italic font-medium text-cyan-300">
	«Hey I write big breast in my prompt but it’s too strong ! My waifu as massive big tiddies.»
</p>
<p>
	Use <code>(big breast:0.9)</code> will be more significant. <br/>
	Tips : you can use a negative value. It’s rare, but some overloader support this. Referee to the notes from the creator.
</p>
<p>
	<h3>Negative prompt</h3>

	The prompt lets you say what you want. The negative prompt lets you say what you don't want.
</p>
<p>
	Don't underestimate the power of the negative prompt. It's a powerful tool for improving the rendering and stability of your prompts.
</p>
<p>
	You can also put Lora, Embedding etc… in negative prompt.
</p>


